  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Sustainable Livelihoods for the Ultra Poor: Nicaragua</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="4">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Provide training and seed capital grants to invest in livelihood activities, and organize community-based savings and credit groups to facilitate continued access to financial resources.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="3">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The extreme poor, particularly women and people with disabilities</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Trickle Up aims to build sustainable livelihoods for extremely poor women through a combination of: training and coaching to help participants plan, expand and diversify their livelihood activities; asset transfers to support new livelihood activities; savings groups to provide a safety net and enable ongoing access to capital; and linkages to public services and preventative health messaging. The program is delivered through partnership with local organizations. Trickle Up works primarily in remote, rural communities, where the majority of the poor rely on seasonal agricultural work that brings in as little as $100 per month, which may be supporting a family of six. The country&apos;s tropical dry zone results in periodic drought and other extreme weather conditions that place further strain on agricultural production and employment. For the poorest, household coping strategies include selling productive assets, withdrawing children from school, or drastically reducing food intake: measures that push households deeper into chronic poverty and compromise health and well-being. Trickle Up is helping the poorest people establish microenterprises that diversify their income streams, broaden goods available in local markets, and build savings that can provide a buffer against economic shocks in uncertain times.</narrative>
  </description>
